  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>Risks & Limitations</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what this DCF might not capture regarding PNC and the broader banking sector.</p>

  <h3>Upside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Interest Rate Environment:</strong> A "higher for longer" interest rate environment can expand net interest margins if deposit betas (the rate at which banks must raise deposit yields) lag behind asset yields.</li>
    <li><strong>Consolidation:</strong> PNC has a history of successful acquisitions (e.g., BBVA USA). Future distressed acquisitions could grow the asset base cheaply.</li>
    <li><strong>Capital Returns:</strong> Banks often return significant capital via share repurchases, reducing share count and artificially boosting per-share value over time.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside Risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Commercial Real Estate (CRE):</strong> Like many regional banks, PNC has exposure to commercial real estate. A sharp downturn or persistent office vacancy issues could spike provision for credit losses.</li>
    <li><strong>Deposit Flight:</strong> The bank run panics of 2023 showed that deposit stickiness is not guaranteed. If deposits flee to higher-yielding money market funds, funding costs will rise, hurting margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Capital Requirements:</strong> Basel III endgame and other regulatory changes could force banks to hold more capital, reducing the return on equity (ROE) and free cash flow available to shareholders.</li>
  </ul>

