  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Is DCF the best way to value a bank?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While DCF is the gold standard for most businesses, banks are often valued using Price-to-Tangible-Book-Value (P/TBV) or Dividend Discount Models (DDM). A standard DCF can be tricky because banks use debt as raw material to create products (loans). However, valuing the pure Free Cash Flow still provides a grounded perspective on the actual cash generation capabilities of the franchise.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 9% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate reflects the required rate of return. With the 10-year Treasury yielding 4.18%, a 9% rate implies an equity risk premium of roughly 4.8%. This appropriately penalizes the cash flows for the macroeconomic and regulatory risks inherent in the regional banking sector.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
